You need to utilise css media queries to target certain breakpoints. Here&#39;s an example


    @media (min-width: 768px){
        .content p{
            font-size: 12px;
        }
    }
    @media (min-width: 992px){
        .content p{
            font-size: 14px;
        }
    }
    @media (min-width: 1200px){
        .content p{
            font-size: 16px;
        }
    }

Ideally, when you start developing a new site, you want to create a style sheet with h1-h6, p, a, ul, ol, etc. Its not good practice to style p tags throughout the site, they should be controlled by one style, in one place. 

If you&#39;re ever working on a 40+ page site and the client comes back and wants to change the parapraph size from 12px-14px, you only have to do this once, not multiple times throughout. Also it follows the DRY principle. 

If you want to target different font sizes you can **encapsulate** the styles. For example, Say your paragraph tag is set to 16px. In the header and footer you want the paragraph tag to be 21px. You can use very similar to your current class. You&#39;re calling the paragraph tag in the .content class, so you need to call the p tag in the .header or .footer class 

So for the header, footer you can use something like this. 

    @media (min-width: 1200px){
        .header p,
        .footer p{
            font-size: 21px;
        }
    }

First, remove duplicate properties that have already been declared in &#39;.content p&#39; from other classes. This will eliminate any chance of having your mobile CSS overridden by these things.

Add a CSS media query right below the &#39;.content p&#39; class to detect the width of the browser and change the font size accordingly. 

    @media screen and (max-width: 600px) {
    .content p {  
    font-size: /* New size here */; 
    }
    }

This will cause the font size to change when a browser&#39;s width is less than 600px.

